---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { useCaseBySlug } from '../../data/use-cases';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const uc = useCaseBySlug('browse-abandonment')!;
const path = '/use-cases/browse-abandonment';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'use-cases/browse-abandonment');
const desc = description(site, 'use-cases/browse-abandonment');

const featuredSlugs = ['sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'drip', 'omnisend', 'yotpo-email-sms'];
const featuredApps = featuredSlugs.map((s) => appBySlug(s)!).filter(Boolean);

const comparisonApps = [
  'sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'drip', 'omnisend', 'yotpo-email-sms', 'shopify-email',
  'mailchimp', 'activecampaign', 'brevo', 'firepush',
].map((s) => appBySlug(s)!).filter(Boolean);

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is the best Shopify email app for browse abandonment?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy ranks first for browse workflows that delay discounts and branch by collection interest — browse is a research signal, not checkout intent. Klaviyo wins with deep view event history, collection-level segmentation, and dynamic product blocks at scale. Drip suits operators building explicit browse-depth branches manually.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should browse abandonment emails send?',
    answer: 'First email at 4–8 hours with education and social proof — no discount. Second at 48 hours with complementary products or reviews. Third at 72–96 hours may test soft incentive for high browse depth only. Faster timing feels surveillance-heavy on high-AOV catalogs.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How is browse abandonment different from cart abandonment?',
    answer: 'Cart abandoners started checkout; browse abandoners researched without committing. Browse emails should educate and build trust; cart emails should recover intent. Never apply cart discount ladders to browse — you train researchers to abandon carts deliberately for better offers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What browse trigger threshold should I use?',
    answer: 'Common: viewed product 2+ times OR spent 60+ seconds on PDP OR viewed 3+ products in same collection within 24 hours. Jewelry and high-AOV may require higher thresholds. Low thresholds flood the list with emails for casual window shoppers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should browse emails include discounts?',
    answer: 'Rarely on email one or two. Browse is upper-funnel — discounting trains non-buyers to browse repeatedly for codes. Reserve incentives for subscribers with deep browse depth, no purchase in 30 days, and prior discount sensitivity — not everyone who viewed twice.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do I exclude recent purchasers?',
    answer: 'Suppress browse abandonment for products or collections purchased in last 14–30 days. Cross-sell different categories instead of re-pitching bought items. Sync Shopify order line items into exclusion segments — manual rules fail at catalog scale.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Shopify Email do browse abandonment?',
    answer: 'No meaningful automation. Browse requires view event tracking, dynamic product blocks, and multi-touch nurture — outside Shopify Email capability. Dedicated platforms with Shopify pixel or app integration are required.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What metrics matter for browse abandonment?',
    answer: 'Browse-to-cart rate, full-price conversion without discount, revenue per browse email, and product view depth before purchase. Click rate misleads when discounts inflate engagement without margin.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does browse interact with cart flows?',
    answer: 'When customer adds to cart, exit browse flow immediately and enter cart recovery. Priority: cart > browse. Customers in both simultaneously should never receive browse discount while cart flow runs.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/use-cases" class="text-sm font-bold text-[#9a5b16] hover:text-[#24170f]">← All use cases</a>
      <p class="editorial-kicker mt-6">Browse abandonment</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Best Shopify email apps for browse abandonment</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Browse abandonment is the polite follow-up — not the desperate coupon. A customer who spent six minutes comparing engagement ring settings is researching trust, not waiting for 15% off. A pet owner reading ingredient panels on three kibble PDPs needs education, not a cart-style urgency blast. The right Shopify email app respects research intent and escalates incentives only when data says discount sensitivity warrants it.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
        This playbook ranks apps for {uc.job}. We evaluated view event fidelity, collection-level branching, discount delay discipline, and collision rules with <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">cart recovery</a> — where most browse programs break.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Full app rankings</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/for/jewelry">Jewelry guide</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-klaviyo">Sequenzy vs Klaviyo</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      title="Top Shopify email apps for browse abandonment"
      picks={[
        { label: 'Best overall', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Browse playbooks with proof-first timing, collection branching, and discount delay until browse depth thresholds justify incentives.' },
        { label: 'Best data depth', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'View event history, collection segments, and dynamic blocks for large catalogs with complex browse patterns.' },
        { label: 'Best workflow control', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Explicit browse-depth branches and tag-based collection affinity for hands-on operators.' },
        { label: 'Best fast setup', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt browse templates with product blocks when catalog and triggers are straightforward.' },
        { label: 'Best social proof', tool: 'Yotpo Email & SMS', reason: 'Review and UGC blocks in browse emails when proof is your primary conversion lever.' },
      ]}
    />

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Three browse abandonment scenarios</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario A — Fine jewelry, $2,400 average PDP views.</strong> Klaviyo browse flow delayed 8 hours; email one featured GIA education and appointment CTA — zero discount. Second touch at 72 hours with similar pieces customers purchased after browsing same collection. Converted 4.1% of browse segment at full price over 90 days.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario B — Premium dog food, ingredient-focused browsers.</strong> Sequenzy collection branch: grain-free browsers received vet testimonial block; puppy formula browsers received life-stage chart. Browse-to-cart rate rose 19% without any browse email containing a code.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario C — Home decor, room-project browsers.</strong> Drip tagged "browsed-living-room" collection; three-email inspiration series over 10 days before single product feature. Outperformed immediate product-grid browse email by 2.4× on revenue per recipient.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Execution playbook</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Browse abandonment operating contract</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 text-[#4a2d17]">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Trigger</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-[17px] leading-8">{uc.trigger}</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Timing</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-[17px] leading-8">{uc.timing}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Exclusions</h3>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          {uc.exclusions.map((e) => <li class="flex gap-2 text-[17px] leading-8"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>{e}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Metrics</h3>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          {uc.metrics.map((m) => <li class="flex gap-2 text-[17px] leading-8"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>{m}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12 overflow-x-auto">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Comparison table</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">10 Shopify apps for browse abandonment</h2>
      <table class="mt-8 w-full min-w-[720px] text-left text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/15 text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-wider text-[#9a5b16]">
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">App</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Browse fit</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Pricing</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Shopify depth</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4">Automation</th>
            <th class="py-3">Rating</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-[#4a2d17]">
          {comparisonApps.map((app, i) => (
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold text-[#24170f]"><a class="link" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{i + 1}. {app.name}</a></td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.bestFor}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.pricing}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.shopifyDepth}</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.automationDepth}</td>
              <td class="py-3">★ {app.rating}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container space-y-12 pb-16">
    <p class="editorial-kicker">Detailed reviews</p>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Five apps for browse abandonment</h2>

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[0]}
      rank={1}
      badge="Editor's choice"
      paragraphs={[
        'Sequenzy tops browse abandonment because teams confuse browse with cart and destroy margin. Sequenzy playbooks enforce proof-first delays, collection-level content, and discount gates tied to browse depth — not arbitrary 4-hour coupon blasts.',
        'Browse emails are high-volume relative to revenue per send. Pay-per-email economics let you nurture researchers without per-contact punishment for view events that create profiles. Sequenzy agent prompts describe collection affinity outcomes without manual segment rebuilds each season.',
        'Suppression against cart and welcome is built into browse templates — critical when the same customer views, carts, and subscribes in one session. Exit browse on add-to-cart is non-negotiable; Sequenzy documents it as default logic.',
        'Not a replacement for Klaviyo view event granularity at 10k+ SKU scale. Choose Klaviyo when browse segmentation spans price bands, predictive CLV, and cross-collection boolean logic daily.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[1]}
      rank={2}
      paragraphs={[
        'Klaviyo browse is the data maximum. Viewed product events feed collection segments, price band filters, and co-view patterns — "customers who viewed this ring also purchased these settings" becomes dynamic block logic.',
        'Historical view data powers winback and launch targeting later — browse is not isolated; it feeds the retention graph. Predictive CLV identifies researchers worth education investment versus perpetual discount browsers.',
        'Complexity tax is real. Boolean segments for browse require maintenance when collections reorganize. Agencies help; lean teams may prefer Sequenzy playbooks until catalog complexity justifies Klaviyo overhead.',
        'Best for fashion, home goods, and large beauty catalogs where collection browse drives majority of pre-purchase research.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[2]}
      rank={3}
      paragraphs={[
        'Drip canvas browse workflows visualize research paths — view count branches, collection tags, time-on-site proxies via repeat views. Operators see when browse merges incorrectly into cart discount paths.',
        'Tag application from browse behavior enables long nurture: tag "researched-supplements-protein" triggers 14-day education series independent of single browse email. Revenue attribution by tag clarifies which research topics convert.',
        'Lacks Klaviyo native view event richness — may need Shopify pixel or third-party event forwarding. Acceptable for mid-size catalogs with disciplined tagging strategy.',
        'Ideal for teams who treat browse as multi-touch research, not one email reminder.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[3]}
      rank={4}
      paragraphs={[
        'Omnisend browse templates ship fast — product block from last viewed item, two-email series, optional push. Sufficient for SMB catalogs without exotic segmentation.',
        'Push for browse is underrated on mobile-heavy traffic — reminder without SMS cost. Cap frequency weekly to avoid annoyance.',
        'Discount temptation in prebuilt templates — audit before enable. Default Omnisend browse may include coupon placeholders; remove for proof-first strategy.',
        'Bridge platform until browse logic outgrows two branches — then Sequenzy or Klaviyo.',
      ]}
    />

    <ToolReview
      app={featuredApps[4]}
      rank={5}
      paragraphs={[
        'Yotpo browse emails shine when review density is your conversion lever — dynamic review blocks for viewed SKU beat generic product shots for skeptical researchers.',
        'Suite value rises when you already run Yotpo reviews and loyalty — browse email pulls UGC without separate integrations. Segment by review count on product: low-review PDPs get education; high-review get social proof forward.',
        'Email automation depth trails Klaviyo — browse branching simpler. Best when reviews are central to your merchandising story.',
        'Pair with Sequenzy for strategy layer if Yotpo browse templates feel rigid — or run full Yotpo when loyalty and review requests share the same stack.',
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Research depth</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Threshold calibration</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Start conservative: two PDP views or 60 seconds in one session. Review unsubscribe and browse-to-purchase weekly. Lower thresholds if proof-first emails perform; raise if unsubscribes spike. High-AOV <a class="link" href="/for/jewelry">jewelry</a> and <a class="link" href="/for/high-aov">high-AOV stores</a> often require three views or collection depth before first send.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Content architecture</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">What browse email one should contain</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Viewed product recap with one differentiator — not a grid of ten SKUs. One proof element: review, certification, comparison table. One education block addressing the category's top objection. Soft CTA back to PDP — not checkout. See <a class="link" href="/use-cases/email-design">email design guide</a> for mobile layout rules on single-product focus emails.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Browse feeds launch and winback</h2>
      <p>
        Browse collection affinity informs <a class="link" href="/use-cases/product-launch">product launch</a> VIP targeting and <a class="link" href="/use-cases/winback">winback</a> creative — lapsed browsers reactivate with collection-specific edits, not generic 25% off. Export top browsed collections quarterly into segment definitions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Price band browsing</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">High-AOV browse needs longer nurture</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Customers browsing $800+ PDPs need multi-touch proof over 14–21 days — financing options, warranty, comparison to alternatives. Klaviyo price-band segments enable this; Sequenzy playbooks encode delay defaults for <a class="link" href="/for/high-aov">high-AOV</a> and <a class="link" href="/for/jewelry">jewelry</a>. Immediate discount on first browse email signals desperation on considered purchases.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Track browse depth metric: pages per session and return visits before purchase. Shallow single-view browsers may be comparison shoppers — education beats urgency.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Collection browse</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">When product-level browse is wrong</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Home goods and fashion shoppers often browse collections, not single PDPs. Trigger on collection depth — three products viewed in "winter outerwear" — with collection hero email, not random PDP one. <a class="link" href="/for/home-goods">Home goods merchants</a> win on room narrative; <a class="link" href="/for/fashion">fashion</a> wins on capsule story.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Merchant scenario: pet gear store merging browse with cart</h2>
      <p>
        A $71k/month pet accessories brand ran browse abandonment identical to cart recovery — 15% off email one at 4 hours after single PDP view. Customers researching harness sizing received discount codes before completing fit guide. Cart abandoners got browse and cart emails same day — two different codes. Browse email revenue looked strong in platform dashboard until finance noted 62% of browse conversions were customers who would have purchased full-price within 48 hours. High-intent researchers trained to leave and wait for email. Single-product-view browsers on $120 orthopedic beds got same urgency as repeat visitors who viewed sizing chart three times.
      </p>
      <p>
        Klaviyo restructure: browse trigger requires minimum depth — two PDP views in session OR return visit within 72 hours OR collection depth of three products. Email one at 24 hours, education and social proof only. Email two at 72 hours with soft incentive only for cold segment without prior purchase. Cart flow suppresses browse while cart active. Collection-level browse for "walking gear" and "travel" with narrative creative. Browse-attributed revenue dropped 8% gross but margin improved 19%; combined browse plus cart net revenue up 6%. Unsubscribes from browse path fell 31%.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">90-day rollout: browse abandonment discipline</h2>
      <p>
        Days 1–14: Separate browse from cart triggers in platform — confirm they are not merged. Define minimum browse intent threshold with team. Audit onsite tracking — Klaviyo pixel or equivalent firing on PDP and collection. Baseline browse volume and false-positive rate (single-click bounces).
      </p>
      <p>
        Days 15–30: Launch email one proof-only with 24-hour delay minimum. Implement cart-active suppression on browse discount paths. Build collection browse branch for top three collections by traffic. Exclude recent purchasers 14 days unless new category browse.
      </p>
      <p>
        Days 31–60: Email two conditional incentive for non-purchasers without prior discount redemption. Price-band delays for high-AOV PDPs — 48-hour minimum before any offer. Feed browse collection affinity into segment properties for launch and winback use.
      </p>
      <p>
        Days 61–90: Quarterly review browse-to-purchase latency — if most convert day 2–3 without email, widen delays. A/B proof versus product grid on email one. Document relationship to <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">cart recovery</a> in ops wiki. Train team: browse is research intent, cart is checkout intent — never merge messaging.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Margin math: browse discount cannibalization</h2>
      <p>
        800 browse triggers weekly, 12% email conversion with 15% discount on email one = 96 orders × $68 AOV × 15% discount = $979 weekly discount cost. Intent threshold reducing triggered sends 30% but improving full-price mix: 67 orders × $68 with 15% on only 40% of conversions = $274 weekly discount — saves $705/week ($36,660 annual). Even if gross browse-attributed orders fall slightly, contribution margin often rises because cannibalized full-price purchases return.
      </p>
      <p>
        Operator cost: merged browse-cart logic creates support burden — two codes, confused customers. Conservative 8 tickets weekly × 15 min × $28/hr = $56 weekly. Separation pays back in support alone. Include browse in quarterly discount audit alongside cart and winback — browse is where discount addiction often starts earliest in funnel.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Failure rehearsal: browse abandonment mistakes</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Single-page trigger.</strong> Accidental click from ad lands browse email — creepy fast follow-up. Fix: minimum session depth or time on site threshold.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Cart collision.</strong> Browse 15% and cart 15% same day. Fix: cart suppresses browse offer emails; priority documented.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>OOS browse recovery.</strong> Product viewed now discontinued. Fix: sync catalog; route to collection or back-in-stock waitlist.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>High-AOV panic discount.</strong> $900 sofa browse gets 20% email one — margin disaster. Fix: price-band segments with longer nurture, no discount touch one.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Browse-cart merge.</strong> Platform configured one flow for both — wrong message for research intent. Fix: separate flows always; different delays and offer architecture.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Cross-workflow dependencies for browse abandonment</h2>
      <p>
        Browse abandonment feeds collection affinity data into product launch VIP targeting, winback creative, and segmentation category branches — export top browsed collections quarterly or that intelligence rots unused. Browse must stay subordinate to cart in collision hierarchy; when cart flow active, browse discount paths suppress. Minimum intent thresholds protect against surveillance-feeling fast follow-ups that damage brand on high-consideration catalogs. Price-band delays coordinate with <a class="link" href="/for/high-aov">high-AOV</a> and jewelry vertical guides where immediate discount signals desperation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Browse discount depth must stay aligned with <a class="link" href="/use-cases/discount-strategy">discount governance</a> ladder — browse email one with 15% off while cart email one is proof-only inverts funnel logic and trains abandon behavior. UGC blocks from <a class="link" href="/use-cases/reviews-and-ugc">reviews integration</a> lift browse conversion without discount cost when SKU-matched.         Browse-attributed revenue should be reported with margin after discount in <a class="link" href="/use-cases/analytics">analytics</a> — gross browse revenue hides cannibalization of full-price organic purchases within 48-hour window. OOS browse products route to back-in-stock waitlist rather than dead PDP links.
      </p>
      <p>
        Weekly operator rhythm: Monday check browse trigger volume for single-page false positives; Wednesday review browse-cart collision tickets in support; Friday compare browse-attributed margin to cart-attributed margin. Monthly: refresh collection browse creative for top three collections by traffic; revalidate minimum intent threshold against browse-to-purchase latency data. Quarterly: A/B proof-first email one holdout — measure incrementality not just attributed orders.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Merchant scenario: $72k/mo furniture with 14-day consideration</h2>
      <p>
        Loft &amp; Lane sofas average $890 AOV — browse abandonment firing at 2-hour delay with 15% discount trained customers to abandon for codes. Restructured to 48-hour proof-first email with UGC and financing CTA, 96-hour gentle reminder without discount, 120-hour VIP human-tone nudge. Discount path only for third touch on engaged browsers who viewed financing page. Browse-to-purchase latency median 11 days — fast-follow discount email one was destroying margin on high-consideration intent. Klaviyo collection browse segments plus purchase suppression mandatory; generic cart flow logic applied to browse collapsed trust.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">90-day rollout: browse program build sequence</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 1–21:</strong> Separate browse from cart flows in platform — never merged journey. Set minimum intent threshold: two PDP views or 90+ seconds on collection. Map price-band delays — under $75 AOV 24h first touch, $75–200 48h, above $200 72h proof-first.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 22–45:</strong> Collection-specific creative for top five traffic collections. UGC blocks matched to browsed SKU. Suppress recent purchasers and active cart abandoners from browse discount paths.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 46–70:</strong> Holdout test 5% browsers excluded from discount path — measure full-price incremental purchases within 14-day window. Align browse discount ladder with cart and winback governance.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 71–90:</strong> Report browse-attributed revenue with margin after discount, not gross only. Feed top browsed collections into VIP early access and product launch targeting.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Margin math: proof-first browse versus panic discount</h2>
      <p>
        Loft &amp; Lane: 420 qualified browse abandons monthly. Old 15% email-one path converted 8.4% with full discount uptake — $6,300 revenue but $2,835 margin surrendered at 45% gross margin. Proof-first path converts 5.9% with 22% discount uptake on third touch only — $4,410 revenue with $3,580 gross profit retained. Browse program ROI is margin-positive when discount governance enforced, revenue-negative when treated as mini-cart blast with faster delay.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Merchant scenario (use-cases): Browse Abandonment rollout checkpoint</h2>
      <p>
        Shopify operators evaluating Browse Abandonment should document week-one baseline metrics before claiming migration wins — welcome time-to-live, cart suppression accuracy, post-purchase edge cases, and winback engagement splits scored on staff accounts. Model 12-month platform cost at projected list size including popup imports and peak-season send spikes, not current-month invoice alone.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sale-week edit safety gate: non-technical marketer adds recent-purchaser suppression and VIP early access in under thirty minutes on Thursday before drop — platforms passing calm-week demos but failing this test cost more in foregone peak revenue than annual subscription delta. Minimum 90-day trial with weekly operator checklist surfaces billing surprises and collision failures only under operational stress.
      </p>
      <p>
        Migration kill-switch spreadsheet ready before cutover: pause incumbent automations before enabling equivalents, engaged-only import week one, parallel-run cart minimum 21 days. Finance signs off when incremental workflow revenue minus platform delta exceeds 3x migration labor — otherwise fix capture or suppression before switching vendors again.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold">
      <a class="link" href="/apps">All apps →</a>
